Greatest Common Divisor: gcd()

(a) Flowchart

Flowchart of gcd().

(b) Pseudocode

Input two values, a and b.
If both a and b are not positive integers,
    Output an error message and stop the algorithm.
Otherwise,
    If a is less than b,
      Switch the values of a and b.
While a and b are still positive,
    Assign the remainder of (a / b) to b, and
    assign the former value of b to a.
Once either a or b becomes non-positive, return the maximum of a and b.

(c) Test Cases (Demonstration of Function & Error-Handling)

gcd(1071, 462) # 21
## [1] 21
gcd(462, 1071) # 21
## [1] 21
gcd(646, 1406) # 38
## [1] 38
gcd(1, 10) # 1
## [1] 1
try(gcd(0, 12)) # ERROR
## Error in gcd(0, 12) : The inputs must be positive integers.
try(gcd(4.5, 12)) # ERROR
## Error in gcd(4.5, 12) : The inputs must be positive integers.
try(gcd(-1, 12)) # ERROR
## Error in gcd(-1, 12) : The inputs must be positive integers.

Prime Factorization: is_prime()

(a) Flowchart

Flowchart of is_prime().

(b) Pseudocode

Input a numeric vector, x.
Create an (empty) logical output vector.
For each element in x,
    If this current element is a (positive) integer and
    is divisible only by two distinct factors (1 and itself),
        Then append TRUE to the output vector.
    Otherwise,
        Append FALSE to the output vector.
When there are no more subsequent elements in x,
    Return the output vector.

(c) Test Cases (Demonstration of Function & Error-Handling)

is_prime(9) # F
## [1] FALSE
is_prime(c(2, 97, 23, 51, 119, -1, 0, 1.5)) # T, T, T, F, F, F, F, F
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE

Prime Factorization: get_factors()

(a) Flowchart

Flowchart of get_factors().

(b) Pseudocode

Input a value, x.
If x is not a positive integer,
    Output an error message and stop the algorithm.
Otherwise,
    Calculate which integers between 1 and itself divide x evenly,
    in order to determine the unique factors of x.
    From these values, extract the elements that are prime.
        [Note: The details of this predefined process can be found above.]
Create a numeric output vector.
For each of our unique prime factors,
    While the current factor divides x evenly,
        Append this factor to our output vector, and
        Divide x by this factor.
If x is not 1 by the end of this process,
    Append x to our output vector.
Return our output vector.

(c) Test Cases (Demonstration of Function & Error-Handling)

get_factors(12) # 2, 2, 3
## [1] 2 2 3
get_factors(1800) # 2, 2, 2, 3, 3, 5, 5
## [1] 2 2 2 3 3 5 5
get_factors(32851) # 7, 13, 19, 19
## [1]  7 13 19 19
get_factors(9587) # 9587
## [1] 9587

## Error in get_factors(-280) : The input must be a positive integer.

## Error in get_factors(280.75) : The input must be a positive integer.
x <- sample(x = 1e4, size = 1)
y <- get_factors(x)
this_works <- prod(y) == x & all(is_prime(y))
